# Wikibench: Capsule Replay and Rubric

## Step

Make edition quality measurable so the pipeline can be tuned parametrically over time — across prompts, models, agents, and harness config — instead of by vibes.

- **Day capsule**: a frozen real day — its observations, prior edition, and metadata — snapshotted so the pipeline replays deterministically-in-inputs without live gather. Capsules are the bench's fixtures; today (2026-07-12) becomes the first one.
- **Replay runner**: run extract → reconcile → build on a capsule, tagged with a config label (prompt contract versions, model), producing a candidate edition for scoring. Real pi calls at run time; never in unit tests.
- **Rubric v1**: deterministic checks first — claim-verifier verdict ratios (correctness), banned-phrase/register scans (voice), all-questions-end-in-"?", shipped-requires-receipt, schema validity (structure), wall time and any token counts the bridge exposes (efficiency). Judged dimensions behind a flag — selection quality and ELI5-technical clarity, scored by a pi judge against a written rubric.
- **Results over time**: append-only score log keyed by capsule + config label + contract versions, with a report that shows the trend. "Did that prompt change help?" becomes a lookup.
- **Baseline**: score the current single-shot pipeline on the first capsule before any newsroom refactor exists — the number the refactor has to beat.

Resolved when a capsule replays, the rubric scores it, a baseline is recorded, and Joel has reacted to the first scored report (the rubric's weights are his taste to set).

## Status (2026-07-12) — built, baseline recorded, awaiting Joel's read

Shipped by the bugle-wikibench pi worker (steered mid-flight with Joel's "checklists KILL thinking" correction — the judge writes its editorial review in prose first, then scores), verified and committed by the steering session (wiki repo `ac3d8ab`).

**Baseline (`baseline-single-shot`, 2026-07-12 capsule):** correctness **36/100** (30 supported, 16 overreach, 0 unsupported, 5 unverifiable — the paper's overreach habit, now a number), voice 65/100 (7 third-person-"Joel" hits, 0 banned phrases, headline clean), structure 100/100, efficiency 85/100 (141s), judged selection **4/5**, judged clarity **4/5**. The judge's review is worth reading in full (in `data/bench/runs/.../`): "the lead is consequential because it catches the paper failing its core job... The weakness is density — too many secondary loops dilute front-page priority."

Known gap: token counts are null (PiBridge exposes model + promptHash, not usage) — efficiency is wall-time only until the bridge grows usage reporting.

Open for: Joel's reaction to the first scored report + rubric weights. The newsroom refactor now has its number to beat.
